abstract: The Legislatiue Caucusses were held last evening, The Whig members of the House met in the Assembly Chambers, T. C. PETERS of Genesee in the Chair. abstract: COLLISION ON THE HARLEM RAILROAD.--A collision accurred last evening on the Harlem Railroad, which was fortunately unattended by serious consequences. The down-rain due at Morrisana at 6 P. M., arrived a few minutes behind time, and after receiving several passengers at that station, delayed some two minutes longer, so that it was overtaken by the next down-train, the engine of which ran half-way through the last passenger car of the forward train.

abstract: COMMON COUNCIL.--The last meeting of the present Board of Aldermen was held on Friday evening. A Committee reported on the application of the Ferry Company for lease of pier at the foot of Fulton-street, re ported in favor of the same. abstract: COMMON COUNCIL.--The Gas Question.--An adjourned meeting of the Common Council was held on Friday evening, Alderman COMSTOCK is the Chair. The special Committee appointed at the last meeting, in reference to the gas question, reported that the gas used in Williamsburg had been analyzed by Mr. Chilton, of New-York, who ascertained that its specific gravity is 480, which is vastly inferior to that of New-York or Brooklyn.

abstract: Governor SEYMOUR'S Message is a failure. He has made it too long by a third--by discussing irrelevant topics, and by continuing to write after he had said all he knew. His introductory column, rehearsing and glorifying the history of the State, is in had taste, and wholly needless. History will take due care of her reputation; and Executive documents ought not to trespass on her domain.

abstract: BRUTAL MURDER BY IRISHMEN.--A most brutal murder was committed in the town of Manchester, at the grocery of RICHARD WHITEHEAD, about 8 o'clock on Monday evening, upon the person of ALEXANDER BRADLEY. It seems that on Monday evening between 7 and 8 o' clock while a large crowd were in the grocery drinking and making merry, four Irishmen, named PAT'K. CROGAN, CORNELIUS CRERY.--DWYER, and--DRISKER, entered the grocery, and purchasing cigars, retired.

abstract: Memphis papers report that the steamer General Bem, bound from this city to Arkansas River, struck a snag in the Mississippi River, at Grand Cut Off, and was torn to atoms in five minutes. She sank to her hurricane deck, when the whole cabin floated off, leaving the hull, with fifteen deck passengers, below the surface of the water, all of whom perished.

abstract: To the Editor of the New-York Daily Times: I trust you will not fail into the vulgar error of attributing the loss of the San Francisco wholly to the gale. abstract: WALLAOK'S THEATRE.--The best written and best acted piece of the season was produced here on Thursday evening. It is called the " Bachelor of Arts," and is from the London boards. The comedy is in three arts, and has but two scenes--two thirds of the play proceeding in the same interior. This is the first instance in our memory where the principal and consecutive parts of a comedy occur in this fashion.

abstract: The Colonization Journal furnishes some statistics with regard to the colored population of New-York City, which must prove painfully interesting to all reflecting people. The late census showed that while all other classes of our population in all parts of the country were increasing at an enormous ratio, the colored were decreasing. In the State of New-York in 1840 there were 50,000; in 1850 but 47,000.

abstract: To the Editor of the New-York Daily Times: I remember seeing in the Paris Constitutionnel, soon after the coup d'etat of December, an article signed by GRANIER DE CASSAGNAC, in which WASHINGTON was styled a selfish, unpatriotic, cowardly dwarf. Similar epithets have been applied by similar men to the noblest men of all ages. The parties which thus seek notoriety by verfying the good, frequently resort for the same purpose, to eulogy of the vile.

abstract: It is beginning to be felt among us, that even the American power of labor has its limits. abstract: The Common Council held a special meeting on Thursday evening, to confer with he Commissioners of Bushwick, upon the proposed plan of converting the Bushwick Creek either into a sewer or canal. This will affect the grades of numerous streets in both Williams burg and Bushwick, which are drained by it, as also the surrounding meadows. A canal will require a filling in of about four feet, while a sewer will take eight.

abstract: The Coroner's Jury, in the case of the Ravenswood Explosion, have brought in their verdict upon the fifteen bodies that were killed thereby. They found that a lamp fed by alcohol was used for heating grease in the same room where there were between 400 and 500 pounds of gunpowder at the same time; and they did not hesitate to say that the explosion was caused by carelessness in the use of the lamp.
